comment: I just completed Day 30, but I wanted to circle back around the Day 1 to offer a testimonial to those of you who are just starting out. I'm the last guy to the toga party-- I mean yoga party. I'm thoroughly middle-aged and congenitally stiff as a dry twig. Thirty days ago, I was nursing a chronic back injury and experiencing a lot of pain from what appeared to be a pinched nerve. Today, not only am I stronger and more flexible, but my back and nerve problems are totally under control. The 30 Day Challenge is a bit like an epic poem. Following its long arc has been a beautiful and moving experience. Thank you.
Who else is doing this for Covid 2020 isolation?

If you‚Äôre just starting out, I hope this helps. Three years ago, I started the 30 Days...and quit after 8 days. During Covid, I decided to try again and it was just what the doctor ordered. I felt improvements by day 5 and soon found myself in life-giving rhythm. This has been a God-send. I‚Äôm in a time of big transition (resigned as pastor, my mom died, launching a coaching business, America in turmoil, etc) but starting each day with Adriene has brought renewal. I feel replenished. I finished the 30 days yesterday and I‚Äôm back to start again today. So...take it easy. Don‚Äôt worry about perfection. Just prioritize the time, show up, and be present. You‚Äôll get results in body and soul. Peace! :D

Just completed day one. Not going to lie I said a couple curse words and got very frustrated that I wasn't able to do several of the positions or whole them for very long, as I am an obese woman. However, after reading through some of the comments made below, I jumped back in and gave it my all. I want to get healthy. I want to do better and I want to be better. I'm hoping this yoga challenge will help me.
There may be a horrible pandemic on, but goddamn my hamstrings are getting flexible

I'm like the last person to even think about doing Yoga, but after months of University work at my desk being hunched over, mixed with quarantine rendering me stiff and inactive, I thought I should treat my body with this.  Hopefully throughout this journey some passersby will come across this comment as I intend to edit this comment daily for the 30 days to share my journey! [Day 30/30]
-
Day 1 - Although light and mellow, there were some poses that were tough for me to do, but I still did them!  This is not in any way a fault of Adriene's for making it 'difficult,' it's just cos I've been so inactive for so long lol.  But after the video ended my body felt warm and my back feels looser!  Already noticing I'm not clicking or creaking as much.
-
Day 2 - Wow I started this with very tight/obstructed hip flexors in the Child's Pose and ended with a completely new flexibility, mobility and 'looseness.'  Also began to sweat which was a surprise for a complete Yoga newbie.  This was significantly tougher than yesterday for me, but in the end felt so good.  Back and hip flexors feel most changed today. 
-
Day 3 - Felt much more different to what I had already done from the past 2 days and it also felt really fast.  Still nice and calming, but personally I hope tomorrow is more like what days 1 and 2 were like!  Feel good overall in terms of agility and flexibility.
-
Day 4 - Now THIS is what I needed, a full on focus for my back.  My biggest reason to even start this challenge was to help loosen my back up and 4 days in, it's done just that.  Felt so good and also (I think I've done it wrong lol but) my heels touched the mat in Downward Dog!  Hope that's a sign of actual progress and not because I've done it wrong lol.  Another great video and personally felt much better than yesterday's.
-
Day 5 - This was 16 minutes?? I swear it only felt like 5 wow this went by so quick.  I felt this was very calming for me, however I was in a happier mood than usual today so that could have influenced my feelings.  Some of the positions were difficult to do, but that's no fault of Adriene's.  It's mine for not getting flexible earlier!  But we're learning I guess lol:)
-
Day 6 - Oh good GOD this one killed me lmao.  Yeah my core strength is effectively zero so this is most definitely the hardest video of the series yet (feel like I'm speaking too soon, but I'm tryna be as transparent as possible).  Really felt engagment in my core and this Yoga session felt much longer to me than yesterday despite them being 16 mins each.
-
Day 7 - Oof man this was tough, but I'm gonna blame my over-indulgence (it was Eid today!).  Probs the sweatiest I've gotten cos of Yoga so far, but it was pretty good.  I feel I would have done better had I not ate so much today lol, but it's all good! Hopefully tomorrow will be better for me personally.
-
Day 8 - This session has really killed my motivation:( it exposed how inflexible I am and I'm metally back to square one with the mindset of 'Yoga isn't for me.'  My hip flexors are still so tight which has demotivated me further because I really thought I was making progress:( I could barely do most of the moves because of how tight my hip flexors are and the cramp I was getting.  Want to give up, but I won't.
-
Day 9 - I think yesterday was an odd blip for me because WOW this felt amazing today! Everything felt so strong, sure they were difficult, but I managed to do nearly everything with good/great form.  There were some minor adjustments to the moves I had to make because of my inflexibility, but I am definitely getting better.  I can also time my breathing better.
-
Day 10 - We're a third of the way through!  I'm so glad I'm starting to do Yoga in the late morning/early afternoon because it nicely sets the tone of my mood and my day.  This was a nice and slow session, felt nice and centred afterwards.  Went by very fast.
-
Day 11 - This felt so incredible for me today wow, I was really focused on all the moves and positions and just feeling every part of my body being really engaged.  I think once this 30 Day challenge is done, I will be coming back to this video daily forever because it targeted where the main site of issue is; my hip flexors.  I felt so much warmer and looser after this, can't wait for tomorrow!
-
Day 12 - This was a nice, slow and soothing session for me.  Very peaceful flow of movements, despite some poses being a little difficult to do!  Managed to keep up with the pace nicely and modified poses for my ability level.
-
Day 13 - The hardest part of this entire session was tryna get your palms to meet in Eagle Pose cos how on earth can you pretzel your arms like that??  Really good session overall though, feeling more and more connected per day and I can't believe it's been nearly 2 weeks of this!  Flown by:)
-
Day 14 - 2 weeks done!  Been a great journey, loved it so far.  This was a nice short session, but man my hamstrings cramped in that new pose:(  Hurt pretty bad, but on the whole this was really nice.  Can't believe we're nearly halfway done.
-
Day 15 - We're halfway through!  So crazy, also sorry for not updating this when I did it yesterday, it was my dad's bday:) but this was definitely the most challenging one so far.  A lot of balance required and I'm not afraid to say I literally toppled over in a few poses hehe.  But it felt really good.  Can't believe we've made it this far!
-
Day 16 - As good as this felt, this was NOT easy OR breezy lol.  It was fast, fluid, intense and sweaty.  But it felt really great.  I'm over halfway into this journey and I'm STILL surprised how sweaty I can get just from yoga!  Really good session today, shower is very much needed hehe.
-
Day 17 - My heels can touch the mat in Downward Dog!  This time with proper form, that is massive progress for me personally and also I was surprised I was able to reach back and grab my arch in that new pose.  Loving how much progress I have made and how agile and flexible I am feeling compared to Day 1:)
-
Day 18 - This felt reaaally good for my hip flexors, which have been thecommon theme of my daily Yoga updates doing this challenge.  I also surprised myself that I actually managed to keep my balance AND bend over in that single-legged forward fold! The stretch that I felt was amazing and literally 2 minutes after it, my hips flexors had never felt so loose!  Amazing session today.
-
Day 19 - This was a very soothing and calming session.  Probably the most connected I've ever felt to my breathing and energy, in my entire life.  Much needed wind-down and relaxation, can't believe we'll be going into the final 10 days from tomorrow!
-
Day 20 - We're in the final 10 days I can't believe it!  Was in a rush today as I was attending a peaceful protest for BLM here today, but this managed to soothe and calm my mind very well.  I even made further progress in my flexibility!  So great to see the progress in myself.
-
Day 21 - 3 weeks officially complete!  I made even more progress here I'm v proud.  Managed to place my palms onto the mat in forward fold with straight legs, I also managed to hold Warrior Pose in near perfect form and I even did the Frog Squat for the first time ever!  And we still have 9 days left to go to make more progress:)
-
Day 22 - Another one that did my hip flexors really well, loved how deep the moves and stretches felt.  Also loved the focus on Warrior Pose movements, they further helped my hips to open.
-
Day 23 - Just one week remaining:( kinda sad it's ending soon.  Anyways,the side plank was quite difficult but I weirdly noticed my balance and strength is greater on my left side than my right.  Strange thing to occur, but just a thing for me to improve on I guess!
-
Day 24 - Wow how strange is it that the first video where Savasana lasted for a few minutes, I didn't even notice.  I was in pure relaxation and stillness until I noticed the gentle music had stopped.  Anyway, this is another video I think I'll be returning to after his challenge is done as it really attacked my hip flexors well!  Another great session, just 6 days remain:(
-
Day 25 - Went by very quick so I decided to take up Adriene's advice of doing one of the options she gave at the end.  I did the hip openers since that's been my main focus and weakness, but other than that it was a nice and easy and mellow session today.  Getting closer to the end now:(
-
Day 26 - This was a nice and calming session and honestly didn't feel that long to me!  Very soothing stretches into different parts of my body that somehow needed to be stretched today, coincidentally, more than ever.
-
Day 27 - This was like a really good test for myself to see how much progress I've made with my flexibility.  And I'm happy to say and see so much progress!  Flat feet in Downward Dog, improved hip motility, deeper Cat-Cow and a lot less stffiness and pain.  This video for me was an amazing progress checkpoint!
-
Day 28 - Wow that flipped Downward Dog was insane, but what's crazier is the fact that I even managed to pull it off!  Felt so good to do a difficult move.  Overall great video again, was great for my entire body and I loved how Adriene gave us a bit more freedom on how to transition into different positions.  It's a nice subtle way to show her build in trust in us over this 30 day journey and to remind us that it's always been us in control, not Adriene:)
-
Day 29 - The penultimate session:( it was another nice video, nothing too challenging or difficult.  Can't believe tomorrow is the last one!
-
Day 30 - Journey complete.  Thank you Adriene for making an average person like me find a new appreciation for Yoga, for guiding a complete newbie and nurturing me the past 30 days and for helping me fix my back and hip flexors.  I'll miss this.

I started doing yoga with you on January 8, 2018.  Honestly I couldn't do a thing, I was about to turn 52, had a big tummy, could barely stretch to touch my knee caps and when I did yoga on the floor, my body shook like a washboard; my big dream was to do downward dog, just. 

I just kept at it; and I increased my time with you just a little every day. Now, here at the end of March 2018, I practice yoga daily.  In fact I'm doing three engagements (day one, two and three) with you a day. So has "Yoga with Adrienne" helped me?  Well I've lost 27 pounds and I look a decade younger.  I've also gotten about 6 other men in their 50's to try doing "Yoga with Adrienne".  Happy to send you a before and after pic (just tell me where to send it).  

Oh one more thing - I'm not done losing weight or feeling good!  I'm actually hooked now because you are such a great instructor.  You have a way of making all of your Yogi's (did I say that right) feel like yoga is the best "feel good" medicine around and it can change anyone's life for the better.  All I can tell you is that your video's have changed mine.

Thank you - and I encourage folks to just, start.

An update:¬†I previously mentioned that I'd started " 30 days of Yoga w Adriene" a few years ago and quit after 8 days; then started up during Covid in a year of big loss and transition for me. I'm now finishing my fourth round of 30 days¬†and I'm so happy. It's just how I start every day now -- part of my "morning rituals."  It's one of the "pandemic positives" that are mine to keep.
As Adriene suggests, we're supposed to become our own guide in time¬†so I don't always follow step for step. Sometimes I turn the audio down and freestyle with the video running for inspiration and to help me when I get stuck.
Also, I went to her website and bought the course. She has a "name your own price" thing, so it supports the cause, is not cost prohibitive and you don't have to watch YouTube commercials. Pretty cool.¬†
So keep up the good work, all. And thank you, Adriene, for helping us find happiness :)

I'm on day 29 and wanted to circle back to describe how powerful, but gentle, this series is. I'm a 65-year-old man with a bit of a belly and I sit at a computer all day long. The first few days had me breathing hard and sweating and I had to take a lot of breaks, huffing, and puffing. 

I told myself, if I make it to Day 5 I'll reward myself with a yoga matt and blocks. No sweat ;-)

As each day passed  I noticed how my body re-adjusted. My movements during the day became smoother, my digestion completely changed (for the better), and my appetite really shifted. I now eat less at each meal which is really cool.

I'm amazed at how this 30-40 minutes each day of being focused and stretching has transformed me.

Adriene is encouraging, gentle, and graceful and is a wonderful guide to the experience of doing yoga for yourself. Her continual reminders of deep breathing with the movement and the suggestions of being playful and smiling really help your mind get in synch. She shows many alternative poses and after every challenging pose, she offers one allowing you to catch your breath and rest. 

Thanks, Adrienne (and your camera person)!  I've now made yoga a regular part of my life. I'm also now a member so I can access your other resources and can continue exploring yoga.

The pain was constant and would wake me at night.  I decided to start on this journey while at the same time scheduling a steroid injection to those nerve roots.  After 7 days of practice, my pain was at a level where I decided to not go forward with the steroid injection.  Now, at 15 days of constant practice I can say that I am pain free!  I will continue this practice moving forward.

Here's how I turned 30 days into 90:
- Repetition: Remember that every practice in life must be done in a conscious way and with repetition; the latter tells you what your body should do and how to correctly do it, the first how to be aware and take the most out of any practice; this will not only teach you how to better practice, but how to be here and now, to be in this moment, the only one that truly exists. I repeated each class 3 times before going to the next, just to take the most out of each day and to do things correctly. This allows you to get a better knowledge of the basics and prepares your body to the most challenging postures. In the end, your body will be ready for anything \o/ (your heels will touch the ground too in downward facing dog in no time!).

Hey fellow beautiful people! This is exam season and with the mounting stress, anxiety and pressure, I decided to do this challenge to keep me physically fit and less stressed. Hope this comment helps me to be accountable and hopefully motivate someone too. Here's my journey so far!

DAY 01- To be honest, it was quite REWARDING to lay down at the end, with the sense of pride to go through the practice but I had to literally push myself so hard to go on. I was trying to get to the next thing every moment and it was much more difficult than I expected to take things slowly and not rushüòî

DAY 02- (attempt #1) I was DYING. I couldn't even complete it. I lack arm strength and my spine is in a horrible condition, making the planks and downward facing dog poses unbearably painful. In addition to that, my feet hurt so much in the beginning under the weight of my body. It made me truly realize how out of shape I really am and makes me worry since I am still too young to not be able to do simple poses. I feel incredibly guilty and demotivated since I had to give up at around 20 minutes of practice but I will try to redo this tomorrow, when I'd be hopefully more energetic and motivated
(attempt #2)- I didn't have time in my schedule to fit in the 30 minutes session and was over all too tired. I feel incredibly guilty for skipping the day ugh.
(attempt #3) Finally finished the 2nd day and feel so motivated, accomplished and overall just so GOOD. The first ten minutes were absolute torture, but being able to finish the session and go through the initial pain, I felt so proud and relaxed as I lay in the shavasana pose. In my opinion, doing this in the morning with the sun streaming through the windows was much easier than at late night and was also more fulfilling to start my day productively with some self care.

DAY 03- Today's session was a whole lot easier and shorter(10 minutes less from the previous one) and the simpler, less painful exercises made the session go by so damn FAST. I couldn't even believe it was over when it was, I wasn't even sweating or being out of breath, which makes sense as this was focused on balance. My balance is absolutely horrendous and the stiffness of my body alarming. I hope to get better by being consistent and I'm glad Adrienne gave us this easier practice to motivate me into keep going, if today was like yesterday, I would have honestly given up but thankfully it wasn't!

DAY 04- I feel like the sessions are getting progressively easier and shorter? Although I'm not quite complaining. The practice was a breeze and I feel more ready to tackle today's exam!

DAY 05- I can't even believe this session was over when it was! It was so short and easy, although I do feel like despite this being for fun and relaxation, I should take this more seriously and push myself a little more than I am rn to see improvement.

DAY 06- I had to take so many breaks today, it was really painful but rewarding. My belly hurt, gave the abdominal muscles a good workout yep. Wow I have completed 1/5th of the challenge! Can't wait to do more.

DAY 07 (attempt 1)- I couldn't do it today because I felt really tired and sick. Looking forward to do it tomorrow tho!
(attempt 2)- this was the most sweating I ever did in this challenge. I had to take sooo many BREAKS it's embarrassing. The side plank was so extremely painful that i tried to do it once and my body screamed in pain, I feel unhappy that I skipped the side planks but oh well. Everyday I realize how far behind I truly am in my body care. My core strength and upper body strength is literally negligible and I can't do push ups for the life of me. I wish I could do push upsüò£

DAY 08- (attempt one) was like 10 minutes in and was bored out of my mind and couldn't focus with disturbing intrusive thoughts swirling around my mind. Will try again tomorrow

I did 30 days of yoga and I wanna share my thoughts and opinion (also I'm commenting here too with the purpose of inspiring new people). I took more than 30 days, like 40/45. Sometimes I skipped from laziness and sometimes 'cause it was the weekend. However i finished all and I'm proud of myself, I feel strong, I feel that I can achieve what I want, my mental health as well as my body's health are improved. I got clarity in my everyday life, I got control over my breath. I know control my body, I used to feel bulky, like an elephant in a jewerly not anymore now and it's crazy how you can improve in just 30 days. If we talk about my appereance, as a man I gain weight over my belly and I definitely see a result there, still something that I have to work on but way more toned and the circumference is decreased for sure (some people even asked me if I lost weight) I see a change on my legs and my butt (my body type is skinny fat). It's October 2020, I took more days than 30, but I still did it and still would do it. I recommend this challenge to everyone, 'cause improved my health in general and now I wanna challenge myself in even more ways. Keep going

So, in April this year (2021), I decided that I wanted to try yoga. I've always wanted to try Yoga, but I've never actually done it before or ever attempted to do it. About mid-April, after my birthday, I went looking for a nice, beginner yoga video and found Adriene's channel, great! I found a nice and simple 20 min (give or take) beginner video, did it, and felt amazing afterward! So, I made it a routine that I would get up and do this 20-minute beginner yoga video each morning. I did this for about two and a half weeks solid with about 3 rest days in between total. And then (whether or not it was related to the yoga or whether I picked up a bag of shopping wrong) but gradually, I felt a seriously sharp pain in my lower back (I'm 24 by the way). I decided to take a few more rest days before doing yoga again but then decided that one more session might help stretch out whatever was hurting, so back to the 20-minute video I went. My god, the pain in my lower back grew sharper and sharper to the point I couldn't breathe without it hurting (I cried at least once every day for a week because whatever I had done hurt that much). Again, I have no idea whether it was yoga-related or whether I had done something else - I think it was picking up a bag of shopping - to aggravate my back; it was a gradual pain that developed rapidly, rather than came on immediately. 
So anyway, my lower back finally felt better about two months after the pain started in April, which takes us to about June 2021. We're in August now and I have been wanting to give yoga another try. I will admit, the pain (wherever it came from) scared me away from yoga. Maybe I don't do it as 'full-on' as I did the first time (as I said, I only did 20 mins in the morning and repeated that every morning bar one or two days, but everyone's body is different and perhaps that was too much for me). So, even though these 30-day videos by Adriene were posted in 2015, I've literally only just seen them today, and saw in the comments that people are saying 'If you're starting out/a beginner this is great.' 
I've got my fingers crossed, I've fished out the yoga mat that I bought back in April and I'm hoping this series of yoga will be good to me! I really, really want to do this and now that I feel I've recovered from my silly, sudden back pain, I want to give it another try. Wish me luck!!

So yoga isn't for ageing grannies? Well that's what I thought but how wrong I was! I'm just revisiting this having completed day 30 today and wanted to go back to the beginning and do it all over again! I'm discovering Adriene has a ton of YouTube videos so now I'm off exploring. I wasn't a complete beginner but I had only done a couple of taster classes so was certainly no expert. I love the way Adriene teaches, she inspires confidence, helps with alignment with detailed descriptors and shows you lots of different levels (plus never makes you feel bad for not being able to do the more difficult stuff!). For me personally, my journey has been so progressive, I am way more flexible (I can sit cross-legged plus can now touch my toes) - might not seem much to some, but after spinal surgery many years ago, I count that as huge progress. I get the 'connection' and 'grounding' too, even the spiritual caught up with me a little. I think about the way I move more, my core is definitely strengthened but the biggest thing I got out of it is that I learned how to breathe! I'd thoroughly recommend giving this a go even if you don't do it every day -  I missed a couple of days, didn't beat myself up, got back on the mat and got on with it. Well worth it and totally inspiring x

Well, I wasn't expecting to burst into tears at the end...that was interesting. haha I started to get emotional when you sent me into the crouching pose and you asked me to think about why I'm committing to this program. I must have been exceedingly mindful, because I went past a wall I had built up. My husband has been on a workout journey for 5 months now. He's gone from over 300 pounds to just over 280. I am 230 pounds. I've been worried that this isn't just a phase he's going through. He's actually doing this and he isn't stopping. I've been very stubborn and resisting his urges to get me doing it too. I've even been resentful of his new healthy habits. Even now, I'm not doing this yoga for him, or even as "exercise", although I do see the benefit. I'm doing it because work is stressful and I feel very tight by the end of the day. But I'm glad I've found your channel. I'm glad for this 30 day challenge. I think I may even *like* yoga! haha I look forward to tomorrow. Day 2, here I come!

Good Morning World.

You may not know but I have been on (what seems like) a life long diet after a motorcycle crash. Also, I am one of those people who live to eat. That also make it a bit of a challenge.

Anyway, I have spent many years in and out of gyms, I hate it. I'm far from a gym junkie, its just one of those things I've needed to focus on. 

But I have always enjoyed classes, especially the yoga and Pilates classes. And found myself in them more than in the gym area itself. 

I have been totally off track for 18months now after two knee operations, and the last two gym's I have been at have not been appealing at all, with either awful or no available classes. 

I am changing gyms again. 

It's brand new but the new one doesn't open until the 7th of September. It also looks like the sort of classes I like to do wont be available. 

At least I know this in advance rather than going in and being let down, so I have found this YouTube page. 

The plan is to get up and do a yoga session, before the visit to the gym. And I have found this 30 Day Challenge.

This morning, I have completed day 1, and already, I feel fantastic. 

To the doubters, yoga is strangely amazing, give it a try. And that comes from a middle aged fat biker with knackered legs.

My aim is to post every day, just to say I have completed each stage of the challenge. This I will do on my Google+ page, any support would be greatly appreciated.

Have a great day world.

About three weeks ago I underwent knee surgery, specifically reconstruction of a torn anterior cruciate ligament. As you can imagine rehab is a lot of lying down in awkward positions due to reduced mobility of the knee, so other parts of my body started getting really sore, especially my back. After this exercise however, even though I couldn't do like half of it since I'm still recovering, I feel like my bones can breathe again. Really awesome. For anyone that's recently experienced any type of orthopedic surgery, I highly recommend you check out this video and do as much of it as you safely and comfortably can. It's a great way to prevent damage to the other parts of your body and add to a really holistic healing process that targets your whole body.
The last time I did this was a decade ago during my middle school days. And now it begins again...

For those who are still debating whether to start - first of all - it doesn't hurt like you think it will. Let's start with that. I am currently at day 7 practice, but i'm practicing for 9 days with Adriene - some days I did twice, and other I did 2 videos in a row - some are just 15 min & I found it not enough for me). And I was a couch potato for about a year before starting. What I've noticed so far: 

My back pain is gone - because of the stretches but also because I started to naturally assume proper posture while walking and sitting. The same with neck pains. 

Downward facing dog is a $%^^$, but only at the beginning, you'll enjoy it later, trust me. 

My daily attitude is better, I am calmer (highly stressful job) and I feel more creative and happy. 

I'm trying to quit smoking, and - this might sound strange - but breathing exercises helps with the cravings. 

My arms and legs feel stronger and though my body doesn't look more fit and muscles toned, I am getting there. 

I genuinely can't wait for the time in a day I reserved for yoga. It's an ultimate relax time!

If you have started and feel discouraged - do it slowly, breathe, huge breathes - it can take you mind off strains in your muscles and it actually helps eliviate them. 

Enjoy it!

Thinking of keeping a comment diary as I do this program.

DAY 1:

So today was my first day, I don't care about doing this in a 30-day month period, I'll just do this from today and into the next month. The practice felt mostly easy, but I did have a light sheen of sweat on my face. Most poses posed no challenges though breathing calmly and getting all the exhales to mirror my moves was hard. The cycle legs and downward dogs were toughest. That final stretch (hug your knee to your heart part) nearly gave me a cramp in my inner left thigh, though my right thigh sailed smoothly. Need to open up my left thigh in general. I had fun, it was relaxing had some challenge. Finding it really hard to keep an upright posture after the workout though, I'm almost falling into the "Mr burns" posture if I relax my back.Looking forward to Wednesday and part 2!

My goal with this series is to become the type of person who shows up for my physical body and mind. I struggle with finding consistancy.  And it doesn't matter what kind of lofty goals I have unless I perfect the art of showing up and make it into a habit. 

Day 1:
I finished all the way through and plan to do day 2 tomorrow at 6:00am right here in my livingroom. Reward for day 1: my body feels stretched out and light.

Day 2: I got up at 5:45am. I completed day two. I'll do the same for day 3. I'll wake up at 6:00am tomorrow and do the 3rd day practice here in my livingroom.

Day 3: I woke up at 5:45am, but didn't get to do Yoga till 8:30am. I'm glad I showed up for the 3rd day. Tomorrow I'll wake up at 5:45am and  do the 4th day practice here in my livingroom.

Day 4: I woke up at 5:30am. I showed up and got it done. I'll do Day 5 tomorrow at 6:00am here in my livingroom.

Day 5: Done! I'll be back tomorrow at  5:30am.

Day 6: Done at 6:am. I'll be back tomorrow at 5:am

Day 7: Done. I got it done at 6:00pm. Tomorrow I'll be back to my morning routine at 5:30am.

Day 8: Done! I'm amazed I kept showing up. Keep it up me! I'll be back tomorrow at 5:30am

Day 9: Done at 7:00am. I'll be back here tomorrow at 6:00am.

Day 10: Done before 7:00am. Same schedule for tomorrow.

Day 11: Done before 6:30am. I'll be back tomorrow :)

Day 12: Done at 6:00am. This might be a record for me. I don't really stick to any physical exercise habits for this many consecutive days.  I'll be back tomorrow. And I'm getting up between 5:00am - 6:00am. I'm in quarantine; I don't have to. But, this makes for productive days.

Day 13: Done before 6:00am. Not only am I showing up everyday, but this is helping me get my day going and not sleep in during these quarantine days.

I suffer from an anxiety disorder and today was one of the worst days I have ever had. I was straight up shaking, had an elevated heart rate while resting and my body was very tense. I don‚Äòt use any kind of medication, so I was at a loss of what to do since my usual coping methods from CBT were not working today. I remembered doing your videos for anxiety and stress about a year ago so I thought, why not start the challenge? So I did. The first half was very uncomfortable for me - not because of difficult poses, but sitting still, mindful breathing and focusing in the moment was so hard for me to do. My anxiety symptoms include shortness of breath, feeling lightheaded and overall physical weakness, which made it so much harder. My CBT includes observing what I‚Äòm feeling and letting go of any wish of controlling my feelings and this practice helped me IMMENSELY! I can‚Äòt thank you enough for guiding me through noticing how my body is feeling and making me feel very comfortable. I can‚Äòt wait to see what Day 2 has in store for me. Thank you Adriene.

I started today. I have been sleeping at the wrong time for the longest time. Ever since the quarantine, I haven't been able to discipline myself. I started to let go of all things I did for my wellness. 

On this day, April 1, 2020, I woke up at 5 am because I was getting bit by a mosquito. 

I lit a candle and started my day with a 10 minute meditation. 
Then I started day one on this 30 day challenge. 

I noticed that my hamstrings were especially tight because I played volleyball with my brother two days ago without warm up, cool down,  or any sort of stretching. 
This was disheartening as I have been practicing karatedo for almost 10 years now. I haven't had training in months. I let go. 

I also noticed tightness on my right upper back. It went away as I went through the day 1 yoga challenge. Then, by the end of the practice, I noticed tightness on my left upper back and shoulder. It is still there at the moment but I am positive that it will be much better in the next few days.

to each their own, but not for me. I've been doing yoga for about 6 years, and i often like to come back to these challenge series because every time you still learn from other people. for instances, six years I've been doing yoga, but when you said "why don't we clasp our fingers in the other direction" for the opposite side of a stretch I was mind blown. I've been doing left/right variations of postures this whole time and had never thought of that. What I didn't like was she gives too many options. Like, yes, as an intermediate/adept you know you can modify postures to suite yourself but for beginners it is extremely confusing to hear "Walk up to a forward fold, from here you can fingerwalk to either side or you can shake the head yes, or-" that's a lot of information for a novice to process all at once. For the sake of a "Day 1" challenge i think the instructor should take more of a firm linear approach. Don't give beginners lots of options, they don't know what to do with them. Let them start getting muscle memory before dropping this way and that ways on them.

Since the sixth day, I've started doing two video's a day: one of the 30 Days-series + one on shoulder, neck or back exercices. Usual time of day is after we've put the kid to bed. Nice and quiet in the house.
An aditional positive side-effect: normally I have to fight the urge to snack in front of the tv. After my yoga-hour, that craving is absent. Is that strange?
I also notice that I'm constantly minding my posture during the day and try to relax and breathe when things get stressy at work, in the car drive,...

So, so far I'm really exited about having finally started basic yoga and am sharing these video's with my friends.

Hiya. I decided to give Yoga a try since I've been suffering from tense, stiff shoulders and also stiff and sore masseter. It's at a point where 80% of the time I can't even try to relax if I just sit down and try to breathe calmly. It doesn't help. Even worse, when I drift towards dream land sometimes I'll have sudden twitch movements in my jaw causing my teeth to clash against each other...sometimes only quietly, but other times so loud it wakes me up (seriously). The latter scenario rarely ever happens, though, according to my significant other my teeth only clash against each other with small force most of the time but very frequently (I don't notice). It's called bruxism but mine is minor. Jaw and shoulders are connected and I'm thinking that my shoulders are probably stiff because my masseter is. If you have any Yoga poses to remedy exactly that issue I'm having, please please let me know.

Now, I don't have a mat and don't have space to accomodate one - I barely have space in my room to practice to begin with. But all Yoga studios unfortunately are too far away, so I'll make the best out of what I've got.

I tried following your instructions and overall I can say it helped. While it didn't remove the stiffness entirely, it did ease it a bit. And considering I probably only did half of the poses correctly that's something :)

I felt some pain and discomfort in my knees during poses that require you to put body weight on them. Also, I'm not sure if some of the poses where quite some weight rests on the palms is really healthy for the hands. Perhaps I'm just doing it wrong?
In any case, I'll be back tomorrow for day 2. :)

Thanks for the session.  It has been a while since I have done physical yoga, I have spent a lot of time lately only focusing on targeted Yogic humming exercises and chakra opening exercises and lucid dreaming.  The beginning is going to take a while since I destroyed the ligaments and cartilage in my right ankle about 10 years ago in an accident and I can sit with one foot in front of the other, but my body has only about 10-15 degrees of movement before my ankle wakes up and screams for mercy.  So I just sit where the pain is manageable and don't push too hard.  

I also recently started a job as a Dishwasher at a major restaurant chain and it is lots of heavy lifting, hot steam and long hours, so my body is in pain everywhere when I get done.  This is a good way to cool down after a shit.  I am noticing that my body has a lot of stored up pain in it from a dislocated hip in soccer practice 20 years ago, I was lucky enough to hit by cars a couple of times while riding electric mopeds in China plus some street fights (12 on 1 the Chinese way) and other accidents while living there, and I am just not in fighting shape any more.  So, it is good that this is light and easy, focusing on the breathing and targeting attention as much if not more than the body postures, since those are very loose interpretations based on personal need.  My body and my mind need this, my heart is urging me to cry myself to sleep as we speak, so it was a good release.  

It has just been a hard and long life with much more violence in it than I care to describe.  We will see how the body and mind and soul feel after your 30 Day Challenge, I have a feeling it will be on a road to recovery and more spiritual openness (some good disciplined activity as opposed to all the mushrooms I have eaten in the last couple of years to break the mind out of its cage and set my adventure on a new course.)
